Grammar

Rule 0     S' -> e
Rule 1     e -> e PLUS t
Rule 2     e -> t
Rule 3     t -> t MUL NUM
Rule 4     t -> NUM

Terminals, with rules where they appear

MUL                  : 3
NUM                  : 3 4
PLUS                 : 1
error                : 

Nonterminals, with rules where they appear

e                    : 1 0
t                    : 1 2 3

Parsing method: LALR

state 0

    (0) S' -> . e
    (1) e -> . e PLUS t
    (2) e -> . t
    (3) t -> . t MUL NUM
    (4) t -> . NUM

    NUM             shift and go to state 3

    e                              shift and go to state 1
    t                              shift and go to state 2

state 1

    (0) S' -> e .
    (1) e -> e . PLUS t

    PLUS            shift and go to state 4


state 2

    (2) e -> t .
    (3) t -> t . MUL NUM

    PLUS            reduce using rule 2 (e -> t .)
    $end            reduce using rule 2 (e -> t .)
    MUL             shift and go to state 5


state 3

    (4) t -> NUM .

    MUL             reduce using rule 4 (t -> NUM .)
    PLUS            reduce using rule 4 (t -> NUM .)
    $end            reduce using rule 4 (t -> NUM .)


state 4

    (1) e -> e PLUS . t
    (3) t -> . t MUL NUM
    (4) t -> . NUM

    NUM             shift and go to state 3

    t                              shift and go to state 6

state 5

    (3) t -> t MUL . NUM

    NUM             shift and go to state 7


state 6

    (1) e -> e PLUS t .
    (3) t -> t . MUL NUM

    PLUS            reduce using rule 1 (e -> e PLUS t .)
    $end            reduce using rule 1 (e -> e PLUS t .)
    MUL             shift and go to state 5


state 7

    (3) t -> t MUL NUM .

    MUL             reduce using rule 3 (t -> t MUL NUM .)
    PLUS            reduce using rule 3 (t -> t MUL NUM .)
    $end            reduce using rule 3 (t -> t MUL NUM .)

